V<<sidebar "Phones and internet abroad">>\u000a<<$- "Cell phones">> GEO doesn't recommend one cell phone provider over another, but there are some resources to help you figure out what is best for you.\u000a\u000aYou may consider leaving your cell phone home and purchasing a cheap phone when you arrive. In fact, that is what we at GEO recommend you do. Or you could buy a cheap unlocked phone before you leave and get the appropriate SIM card when you arrive in your host country. (Some airports sell SIMs in the international arrivals section, so they can be quite easy to come by.)\u000a\u000aIf you do plan to take your own phone abroad, be sure to check with your phone company about their international plans and rates. Also check their data-roaming fees, since those can rack up fast!\u000a\u000aYou may want to talk to your provider (or look at their predeparture materials) to see if they have specific recommendations on how to handle phones abroad. You can also visit the Independent Traveler [[international cell phone guide|http://www.independenttraveler.com/travel-tips/stay-connected/international-cell-phone-guide]] to get a good overview of the options.\u000a\u000a<<$- "Dialing Telephones">> The details of dialing internationally vary depending on which countries you're trying to connect. Check out [[How To Call Abroad|http://www.howtocallabroad.com/]] and share it with family and friends.\u000a\u000a<<$- "Internet">> Internet access abroad is typically not the same as in the US. While you will have access, prepare yourself for slower connections. Depending on your host location, you might have a weekly usage limit in your room or at your college, or you may need to pay for internet access at a cafe. Talk with your program provider or host university to find out what to expect.\u000a\u000a<<segue "Disabilities and accommodations">>\u005c
